4. The Color-Singlet Component In this section we explain our calculation in detail for J = 1 and simply give the results for J = 0; 2. As mentioned in Sect. 3 we will use the color singlet wavefunction to project out the 3P1 color singlet Q _Q state. In order to present the Feynman diagrams in the calculation efficiently, we decompose the function DH=G(z) as:

DH=G(z) , TH \Omega T yH : (4:1) Here the symbol \Omega denotes contractions of color- and Lorentz-indices and summations over all possible intermediate states. Such a decomposition is always possible by sandwiching

7

the operator PX jX ?! Xj between ayH and aH in the definition in Eq.(2.1). TH may be called fragmentation amplitude.

The color-singlet component DO/J =G;1(z) becomes nonzero at the order of ff2s. The Feynman diagrams for TH are given in Fig.3. Since the Q _Q pair is in a color singlet state, there must at least be two gluon lines attaching the quark line. There is a I.R. divergence if the energy of the gluon exchanged between two quarks becomes zero. This results a singularity in DO/J =G;1(z) at z = 1. We use dimensional regularization to regularize this I.R. divergence. The calculation is tedious but straightforward. We obtain:

