The _-dependence in the color-singlet component ^D1(z; J ) is compensated by that in the matrix element of OO/J8 (3S1) through the renormalization group equation in Eq.(3.5).

13

At order of ff2s the nonzero contribution to the r.h.s. of Eq.(5.11) is only from gluon fragmentation function because quarks can not fragment into the quarkonium at order of ffs. Substituting the lowest order result of the gluon fragmentation function into the r.h.s. in Eq.(5.11) we find after a little algebra, that our fragmentation function satisfies Eq.(5.11) at order of ff2s. Here we make some comments on the results for the fragmentation of c-quark into O/cJ given in [8]. Since a gluon can decay into 3PJ quarkonia at order of ffs, there must be a _-dependence in the function of the quark fragmentation into 3PJ quarkonia at order of ff2s according to the Altarelli-Parisi equation. However, from the results in [8], there is no _-dependence at this order. Hence the results in [8] for c quark fragmentation into O/cJ are not correct. A new calculation is needed and is already on the way[17], where it is realized that light quarks can also decay into 3PJ quarkonia through the color octet Q _Q state at order of ff2s.

From our results we can see that the gluon fragmentation functions behave like z\Gamma 1 as z ! 0. This is expected in general or simply from the evolution equation (5.11) and (5.12). However, our results tell us that at the scale _ = 2M such behaviour disappears.

6. Discussion and Summary

To discuss possible impact of our results for 3PJ quarkonium production, we calculate the first moment M (0) of the fragmentation functions. This moment is the probability to find a quarkonium without observing its momentum in a jet initialized by a gluon. A rough estimate for 3PJ quarkonium production due to fragmentation can be made by taking the product of parton cross sections and the first moments of the partons. We take the c quark as an example. We neglect the heavy flavor, i.e. b and t quark and take Nf = 4 and mq = 0 for light flavors. To avoid the singularity at z = 0, we calculate the moments at _ = 2Mc. We obtain:

M (0)(G ! O/c0) = 1M 3

c ! 0jO

O/c0 8 (3S1)j0 ? \Delta \Gamma 0:131ffs(2Mc) + 0:537ff2s(2Mc)\Delta

\Gamma 0:067ff2s(2Mc) 1M 5

c ! 0jO

O/c0 1 (3P0)j0 ?;

M (0)(G ! O/c1) = 1M 3

c ! 0jO

O/c1 8 (3S1)j0 ? \Delta \Gamma 0:131ffs(2Mc) + 0:537ff2s(2Mc)\Delta

\Gamma 0:021ff2s(2Mc) 1M 5

